ENTRY            A0459   20260202   20260327   20260327       A130
SUBENT        A0459001   20260202   20260327   20260327       A130
BIB                 13         51
TITLE      Complete and incomplete fusion reactions in the
           12C + 169Tm
AUTHOR     (S.Chakrabarty, B.S.Tomar, A.Goswami, G.K.Gubbi,
           S.B.Manohar, Anil Sharma, B.Bindukumar, S.Mukherjee)
INSTITUTE  (3INDTRM,3INDVUU)
REFERENCE  (J,NP/A,678,355,2000)
FACILITY   (VDGT,3INDTRM)
SAMPLE     For the excitation function measurements,
           self-supporting metal foils of thulium having thickness
           around 1 mg/cm2 backed by 2 mg/cm2 thick aluminium
           catcher foils were bombarded with 12C beam. In each
           irradiation a stack of two such target catcher
           assemblies was used.
DETECTOR   (HPGE)
METHOD     (STTA,ACTIV) The duration of irradiation was about one
           hour with the total charge collection of about 400 muC.
           (BCINT) Measured using an electron suppressed Faraday
           cup placed behind the target-catcher assembly.
           (GSPEC) The time elapsed between the stoppage of beam
           and the start of counting of the sample on detector
           was about 5 minutes. Thus the excitation function
           measurements could be carried out only for
           evaporation residues having half-life more than 5 min.
           Initially the counting time was kept as 100 sec.
           and was subsequently increased to longer periods for
           counting long-lived products.
COMMENT    -By authors. The radioactivity produced due to
           bombardment of aluminium catcher foil by the 12C beam
           is due to 146 keV gamma-ray of 34Cl-m which has a
           half-life of 32 min. This does not interfere with
           gamma-ray energies of interest. All other reaction
           products of 12C + 27Al do not have suitable half
           lives or gamma-rays so as to cause any interference
           with the gamma-rays of interest.
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-T) The errors on the cross section values are
           in the range of 10-20%.
           (ERR-1) The major factors contributing to the errors
           are that due to the target thickness (5%),
           (ERR-2) Uncertainty due to detection efficiency (5%)
           (ERR-3,1.,15.) Statistical and fitting error on the
           peak area (1-15%).
ADD-RES    (RANGE)
           Complete and incomplete fusion cross sections for some
           products.
STATUS     (TABLE,,S.Chakrabarty+,J,NP/A,678,355,2000)  Data from
           authors. Values presented on figs in the article.
HISTORY    (20021220C)
           (20030123R) Data tables are received from S.Chakrabarty
           (20030714A) Subentry A0459008 is corrected.
           (20030715U) Last checking has been done.
           (20260202A) SD: Corrections in Subents 001, 008.
ENDBIB              51
COMMON               3          3
EN-ERR     ERR-1      ERR-2
MEV        PER-CENT   PER-CENT
        1.1        5.         5.
ENDCOMMON            3
ENDSUBENT           58
